To download our App on an Apple device click here: Sunday Tribune on iTunesTo download our App on an Android device click here: Sunday Tribune on Play StoreDURBAN -  A mass meeting to address crime in Chatsworth was held on Wednesday night at the town’s Nelson Mandela Youth Centre. The meeting drew dozens of concerned residents who lashed out at government representatives on the events of Monday night, where armed police fired at protesters.The protest came in the wake of the killing of Sadia Sukhraj, who was killed in a botched hijacking when she was shot in the stomach. Three armed hijackers had hijacked the 9-year-old's father, Pastor Shuleindra Sukhraj, and a shootout ensued. One alleged hijacker was shot dead at the scene, one was arrested and another is at large.The meeting was convened by Public Works MEC Ravi Pillay, who called for a more co-ordinated and effective crime-fighting effort, in the aftermath of the tragic Shallcross shooting.ALSO READ: Sadia Sukhraj - court appearance moved to Durban over security concerns 					Police threaten, swear and manhandle our female journalist 					LISTEN: This heartfelt message to Sadia's parents will make you cry After Pillay, KwaZulu-Natal Member of Parliament Maggie Govender, and Chatsworth Community Policing Forum chairperson Jakes Singh addressed the meeting, civilians' hands shot up in a bid to have their say.Much of the discussion during the question and answers session revolved around increasing police visibility in Chatsworth via satellite stations, and having investigations into the protest that unfolded on Monday night.Watch below, five moments that stunned those in the community meeting:1. 	Denise Govender, whose husband was shot dead last year, told the crowd how local leaders visited her and took pictures but yet the case is still being investigated. 













